        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> To me this seems a bit strange because `Client:on_attach` and with it `_text_document_did_open_handler` is already guarded by `attached_buffers` (except for the on_reload case).\r\n> \r\n> Adding a second state map to guard it a second time feels off. Can you double check why the existing guards aren't sufficient for the given case?\r\n\r\nYou're right, after digging deeper I agree this PR is not the right fix.\r\n\r\nSome context on what led me here: I was getting Roslyn LSP server crashes when navigating to `.cs` files via Telescope. \r\ni even tried to fix this directly in the roslyn.nvim plugin: https://github.com/seblyng/roslyn.nvim/pull/327\r\nThe LSP log showed:\r\n\r\n```\r\nSystem.InvalidOperationException: didOpen received for file:///path/to/file.cs which is already open.\r\n```\r\n\r\nRoslyn crashes hard on duplicate `didOpen` instead of ignoring it, which is technically correct per the LSP spec. I traced it to Telescope triggering `BufEnter` multiple times, causing Neovim to send `didOpen` twice for the same URI. I had a working workaround wrapping `client.rpc.notify` in a `LspAttach` autocmd to deduplicate notifications at the RPC level (similar to the pr i made in roslyn.nvim), which led me to think this should be fixed here in neovim.\r\n\r\nHowever, after your comment I compiled Neovim from source at the exact same tag as my system package (v0.11.6) and the bug doesn't reproduce not even without my fix. I tried matching every build flag from the Arch PKGBUILD (`USE_BUNDLED=OFF`, `ENABLE_TRANSLATIONS=ON`, Ninja generator, same `RelWithDebInfo` flags, same system libraries) and still can't reproduce it with a self-compiled binary.\r\n\r\nSo I honestly don't know why the Arch-packaged binary behaves differently from a binary compiled from the same source. The existing `attached_buffers` guard seems sufficient when compiled from source, just as you suspected. for now i will stick wit the autocmd workaround in my nvim config files....\r\n\r\nI'll close this PR. The issue seems specific to my environment rather than a general Neovim bug.",
